{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = The Hundred-Year Christmas | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:Hundred year christmas.jpg | caption = Dust-Jacket from the first edition | author = [[David Morrell]] | illustrator = R. J. Krupowicz | cover_artist = R. J. Krupowicz | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Fantasy novel]] | publisher = [[Donald M. Grant, Publisher, Inc.]] | release_date = [[1983 in literature|1983]] | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 72 pp | isbn = 0-937986-57-7 | oclc = 11495705 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Hundred-Year Christmas''''' is a [[fantasy novel]] by [[David Morrell]], who is best known for being the creator of [[John Rambo]] in his earlier novel ''[[First Blood (novel)|First Blood]]''.<ref name="thrillerwriters">{{cite web |url=http://www.thrillerwriters.org/2009/11/the-hundred-year-christmas-and-the-spy-w.html |title=The Hundred-Year Christmas, and The Spy Who Came for Christmas by David Morrell |author=Dionne, Karen |work= |publisher=International Thriller Writers |accessdate=2009-12-13}}</ref> ''The Hundred-Year Christmas'' was first published in [[1983 in literature|1983]] by [[Donald M. Grant, Publisher, Inc.|Donald M. Grant]] in an edition of 700 copies, which were signed and numbered.
==Origin== The novel was originally written as a Christmas present for Morrell's two children,<ref name="thrillerwriters"/> and the children in the novel are named after Morell's son and daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidmorrell.net/books/dsp.book.cfm?bid=27 |title=The Hundred-Year Christmas (1983) |author= |work= |publisher=The David Morell Network |accessdate=2009-12-13}}</ref>
==Plot== The novel concerns the friendship between [[Father Christmas]], who lives for 100 years, and [[Father Time]], who lives for only one. Each year Santa Claus watches a new version of his friend grow old and die, before being replaced; however, Santa's hundred years is up and it is now his turn to find a replacement. If he fails then no one will be around to take care of the infant Father Time and time itself will stop.<ref name="thrillerwriters"/>
==Reception== ''The Hundred-Year Christmas'' was nominated for a [[World Fantasy Award]] in 1984 for best short story.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/m/david-morrell/ |title=David Morrell |author= |work= |publisher=Fantastic Fiction |accessdate=2009-12-13}}</ref>
